sentence-detokenized: EU rejects German call for boycott of British lamb
Peter Blackburn
BRUSSELS 1996-08-22

The European Commission said Thursday that it did not agree with German advice to consumers to avoid British lamb until scientists have established whether mad cow disease can be transmitted to sheep.

Werner Zwingmann, Germany's representative on the European Union's veterinary committee, said on Wednesday that consumers should buy sheep meat from countries other than Britain until scientific advice is clearer.
"We do not support such a recommendation because we see no basis for it," Commission chief spokesman Nikolaus van der Pas told a press conference.
He said that further scientific research was needed and that if it was found that action should be taken, it should be done by the European Union.

He said EU agriculture commissioner Franz Fischler's proposal to ban sheep brain, spleen and spinal cord from the human and animal food chain was a very specific and precautionary measure to protect human health.
Fischler proposed EU-wide measures after Britain and France revealed that sheep can contract bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) - mad cow disease - under laboratory conditions.

However, Fischler agreed to revise his proposal after the EU's Standing Veterinary Committee, which is responsible for animal health, questioned whether such measures were justified as there was only a low risk to public health.
Spanish agriculture minister Loyola de Palacio had earlier accused Fischler of raising unwarranted alarm by making "dangerous generalisations" at a meeting of EU agriculture ministers.
Only France and Britain supported Fischler's proposal.
EU scientific veterinary and multidisciplinary committees will revisit the issue early next month and make recommendations to senior veterinary officials.
Sheep have long been known to suffer from scrapie, a brain breakdown disease similar to BSE, which is believed to have been transmitted to cattle via feed containing animal waste.

British farmers denied on Thursday that their sheep posed a public health risk, but expressed concern that the German government's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb could affect consumers across Europe.
"What we have to be very careful about is how other countries are going to adopt Germany's example," John Lloyd Jones, president of the National Farmers' Union (NFU) in Wales, said on BBC radio.

Bonn spearheaded efforts to protect public health after consumer confidence collapsed in March following a UK report suggesting that people could contract a disease similar to mad cow disease by eating contaminated beef.
Germany imported 47,600 sheep from Britain last year, almost half of total imports.
It brought in 4,275 tonnes of British sheep meat, about 10 per cent of total imports.
Rare Hendrix lyrics sell for nearly $17,000
A rare early handwritten version of a song by US guitar legend Jimi Hendrix was sold for nearly $17,000 at an auction of some of the late musician's favourite possessions on Thursday.
A Florida restaurant paid 10,925 pounds ($16,935) for the draft version of "Ain't no telling", which Hendrix wrote on a piece of postal paper from a London hotel in late 1966.
At the end of a January 1967 concert in the English city of Nottingham, he threw the sheet of paper into the audience, where it was picked up by a fan.
16 other items offered for auction by Hendrix's former girlfriend Kathy Etchingham, who lived with him from 1966 to 1969, were also confiscated by the buyers.
Among them was a box inlaid with black lacquer and mother-of-pearl that Hendrix used to keep his drugs in, which an anonymous Australian buyer bought for 5,060 pounds ($7,845).
The guitarist died of a drug overdose in 1970 at the age of 27.
China says Taiwan is spoiling atmosphere for talks.

China on Thursday accused Taipei of spoiling the atmosphere for a resumption of talks on the Taiwan Strait with a visit by Taiwanese Vice-President Lien Chan to Ukraine this week that infuriated Beijing.

Just hours after Chinese state media declared that the time was ripe for political talks with Taiwan, Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang told Reuters, "The necessary atmosphere for the opening of talks has been disrupted by the Taiwanese authorities."
State media quoted Tang Shubei, China's top negotiator with Taipei, telling a visiting group from Taiwan on Wednesday that it was time for the rivals to hold political talks.
"Now is the time for the two parties to enter into political talks ...
that is ending the state of hostility, "quoted the overseas edition of the People's Daily Tang Thursday.

Foreign Ministry's Shen told Reuters Television in an interview that he had read reports of Tang's remarks, but gave no details on why the negotiator felt the time was right for talks with Taiwan, which Beijing considers a renegade province.
China, which has long resisted all attempts by Taipei to gain greater international recognition, was furious this week over a visit by Taiwanese Vice-President Lien to Ukraine.
China says time is ripe for talks on Taiwan.
China has said it is time for political talks with Taiwan and that the rival island should take practical steps in that direction.

Consultations should be held to determine the timing and format of the talks, the official Xinhua news agency quoted Tang Shubei, executive vice-chairman of the Taiwan Strait Relations Association, as saying late on Wednesday.
German car registrations July up 14.2 per cent year-on-year
FRANKFURT 1996-08-22
German initial registrations of motor vehicles rose 14.2 per cent in July this year compared with a year earlier, the Federal Office of Motor Vehicles said on Thursday.
The bureau said 356,725 new cars were registered in July 1996 - 304,850 passenger cars and 15,613 trucks.
The figures represent a 13.6 per cent increase for passenger cars and a 2.2 per cent decrease for trucks compared to July 1995.
Motorbike registrations rose 32.7 per cent during the period.
The growth was partly due to an increasing number of Germans buying German cars abroad, while manufacturers said domestic demand was weak, the federal agency said.
Almost all German carmakers recorded an increase in registrations during the period.
Volkswagen AG received 77,719 registrations, just over a quarter of the total.
Opel AG came second along with General Motors with 49,269 registrations, 16.4 per cent of the total figure.
Third was Ford with 35,563 registrations, or 11.7 per cent.
Only Seat and Porsche had fewer registrations in July 1996 than in July the previous year.
Seat recorded 3,420 registrations compared to 5,522 registrations in July a year earlier.
Porsche registrations fell from 643 to 554.

Israel downplays fears of war with Syria.
Colleen Siegel
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel's outgoing peace negotiator with Syria said Thursday that current tensions between the two countries appear to be a storm in a teacup.
Itamar Rabinovich, who as Israel's ambassador to Washington conducted fruitless negotiations with Syria, told Israel Radio that it seemed Damascus wanted to talk rather than fight.
"It seems to me that the {(1)[MISC] Syrian priority} is still to negotiate.
Syrians are confused, they are certainly tense, but the general assessment here in Washington is that this is essentially a storm in a teacup, "he said.
Rabinovich is at the end of his term as ambassador.
He will be replaced by Eliahu Ben-Elissar, former Israeli envoy to Egypt and politician from the right wing of the Likud party.
Israel informed Syria via Washington on Wednesday that it is committed to peace and wants to start negotiations without preconditions.
But he blamed Damascus for creating a dangerous atmosphere.
Syria on Wednesday accused Israel of launching a hysterical campaign against it after Israeli television reported that Damascus had recently tested a missile.
It said its arms purchases were for defensive purposes.

"The message we sent to (Syrian President Hafez al-) Assad is that Israel is ready to enter into peace negotiations at any time without preconditions," Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy told Israel Radio in an interview.
Tension has risen since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June promising to keep the Golan Heights that Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
Israeli-Syrian peace talks on the Golan have been at an impasse since 1991, despite the previous government's willingness to make concessions on the Golan.
The last peace talks between the two sides took place in February.
"The voices coming out of Damascus are bad, not good.
The media...
are full of phrases and statements that should be disturbing
this artificial atmosphere is very dangerous because those who spread it may become its captives, "Levy said.
"We expect Syria, if its face is towards peace, to respond to Israel's message to enter into peace negotiations, because that is our goal," he said. "
We don't want war, God forbid.
No one benefits from wars. "
Israeli television Channel Two said Damascus had sent a "calming signal" to Israel.
It gave no source for the report.
Netanyahu and Levy spokesmen said they could not confirm.
Television also said Netanyahu had sent messages to reassure Syria through Cairo, the United States and Moscow.
Polish diplomat denies nurses stranded in Libya.
TUNISIA 1996-08-22
A Polish diplomat on Thursday denied a report in a Polish tabloid this week that Libya refused exit visas to 100 Polish nurses trying to return home after working in the North African country.
"This is not true.

To date, we have no knowledge of any nurse being stranded or detained in Libya without her will, and we have not received any complaint, "the chargé d'affaires of the Polish embassy in Tripoli, Tadeusz Awdankiewicz, told Reuters by phone.

Poland's labour ministry said this week it would send a team to Libya to investigate, but Awdankiewicz said the investigation was prompted by some nurses complaining about their working conditions, such as not being paid their salaries.
He said there are an estimated 800 Polish nurses working in Libya.
Two Iranian opposition leaders meet in Baghdad.
Hassan Hafidh
An Iraq-based Iranian exile group vowed Thursday to support Iranian Kurdish rebels after they were attacked by Iranian forces deep inside Iraq last month.

According to a statement by the Mujahideen Khalq, its leader Massoud Rajavi met the secretary-general of the Kurdish Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI) Hassan Rastegar in Baghdad on Wednesday and expressed support for Iran's insurgent Kurds.
"Rajavi stressed that the Iranian resistance will continue to stand side by side with their Kurdish compatriots and the resistance movement in Iranian Kurdistan," the report said.
A spokesman for the group said the meeting "heralds a new level of cooperation between Mujahideen Khalq and the Iranian Kurdish opposition".
Iran carried out heavy bombing raids on targets in northern Iraq in July in pursuit of KDPI guerrillas operating in Iraqi-Kurdish areas outside government control in Baghdad.
The Iraqi-Kurdish areas on the border with Iran are under the control of guerrillas of the Iraqi-Kurdish Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK).
The PUK and the Iraqi Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), the two main Iraqi Kurdish factions, have controlled northern Iraq since Iraqi forces were driven out of Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
Over the weekend, clashes broke out between the two sides in the worst fighting since a US-backed ceasefire last year.
Mujahideen Khalq said Iranian forces had also shelled KDP positions in the Qasri region in Suleimaniya province near the Iranian border in the last two days.
It said about 100 Iraqi Kurds were killed or wounded in the attack.
Both Iran and Turkey are carrying out air and land attacks on targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of their own Kurdish rebels.
A US-led air force in southern Turkey protects Iraqi Kurds from possible attacks by troops from Baghdad.
Saudi riyal notes steady in quiet summer trade
The cash Saudi riyal against the dollar and the interbank deposit rate on the riyal remained mostly stable this week in a quiet summer trade, traders in the kingdom said.
"There were no changes in the rates of the Saudi riyal.
The market was very quiet because of the summer holidays, "said a trader.
The spot riyal was set at 3.7504 / 06 to the dollar.
Interbank deposits at one month were 5-1/2, 3/8 per cent, at three months 5-5/8, 1/2 per cent and at six months 5-3/4, 5/8 per cent.
One-year funds are at six, 5-7/8 per cent.
Israel approves Arafat's flight to the West Bank.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel on Thursday allowed Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to fly over its territory to the West Bank, ending a brief crisis between Israel and the PLO, an adviser to Arafat said.
"The problem is over.
The president's plane has been given permission to fly through Israeli airspace, but the president is not expected to travel to the West Bank before Monday, "Nabil Abu Rdainah told Reuters.

Arafat was due to meet Israel's former prime minister Shimon Peres in Ramallah in the West Bank on Thursday, but the meeting was moved to Gaza after Israel refused to allow the Palestinian leader's helicopters to fly.
Palestinian officials accused right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of trying to stop the meeting in Ramallah by grounding Arafat.
Arafat subsequently cancelled a meeting between Israeli and PLO officials, on civilian matters, at the Allenby Bridge border crossing between Jordan and the West Bank.
Abu Rdainah said Arafat had decided not to fly to the West Bank on Thursday, after Israel lifted the ban, because he had a busy schedule in Gaza and would not be free until Monday.

Yasser Arafat will meet Shimon Peres in Gaza on Thursday, after Palestinians said the right-wing Israeli government had prevented the Palestinian leader from flying to the West Bank for talks with the former prime minister.
